GoFundMe Analysis of Backers

projects = read.csv("../../data/processed/gofundme_projects_clean.csv")
projects$month = factor(projects$month)
projects$day_of_week = factor(projects$day_of_week)
nrow(projects)
## [1] 5223

In total, we have N=5223 IID samples to work with.

Removed all random variabes except year because they didnâ€™t help explain any variance in the data beyond what the residuals could capture. Year is a reasonable random effect as well (see Variance Components, Searle et al 2006)

Nesting and Chi2 differences: https://www.psychologie.uzh.ch/dam/jcr:ffffffff-b371-2797-0000-00000fda8f29/chisquare_diff_en.pdf

Number of Backers

nrow(projects[projects$backers > 1000, ])
## [1] 35
ggplot() + labs(x="Number of Backers", title="Number of Backers Density") +
  geom_density(aes(projects$backers[projects$backers < 1000]))

We limit to 1000 because removing the outliers leaves us with a nicely shaped distribution.

projects.b <- projects[projects$backers < 1000, ]

Run a quick data dispersion test (see Rice 1995):

s = na.omit(projects.b)
pchisq(2 * sum(projects.b$backers * log(projects.b$backers / mean(projects.b$backers))), length(projects.b$backers) - 1, lower.tail = F)
## [1] 0

H0: The data are fit well by a Poisson Distribution H1: Poisson fails to fit the data well

The Poisson distribution obviously does not fit the data well since p approx 0. Letâ€™s use a NegBin instead, which can account for differences in the mean and variance.

Model backers

It might be the case that a quasi-Poisson model fits better, see: https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1141&context=usdeptcommercepub

Here, negative binomial has a lower residual deviance than quasi-poisson. Therefore we use NegBin.

Inherently, the number of backers must be > 0, thus we model using a truncated NegBin fit.

backers.formula.base = backers ~ shares_sc + friends_sc + updates_sc + photos_sc + goal_sc + text_length_words_sc + duration_float_sc + cancer_type + month + day_of_week + (1|year)

backers.mod.base = glmmTMB(backers.formula.base, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2")
# drop1(backers.mod.base, test="Chisq")
backers.formula = update(backers.formula.base,  ~ . - day_of_week)
# drop1(glmmTMB(backers.formula, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2"), test="Chisq")
backers.formula = update(backers.formula,  ~ . - friends_sc)
# drop1(glmmTMB(backers.formula, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2"), test="Chisq")
backers.formula = update(backers.formula,  ~ . - month)
# drop1(glmmTMB(backers.formula, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2"), test="Chisq")
backers.mod = glmmTMB(backers.formula, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2")

Add metaphors

Set up functions used later to simplify metaphor reporting

p = function(var, scl=1, digits=6, mult=1.00, mask=T) {
  mu = mean(projects.b[mask, var])
  sd = sd(projects.b[mask, var])
  print(glue("Var: {var}\t Mean: {round(mu,digits)*scl}\t SD: {round(sd,digits)*scl}\t Scale (x{round(mult, 2)}): {paste(round(mult*sd + mu, digits)*scl)}"))
}
p("journey_salience", scl = 1000, digits = 5, mult = 0.6)

addMetaphors = function(formula, refit, model) {
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + any_metaphor), "any_metaphorTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + both_metaphor), "both_metaphorTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + dom_journey), "dom_journeyTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + dom_battle), "dom_battleTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + only_battle), "only_battleTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + only_journey), "only_journeyTRUE", model)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + scale(battle_salience)), "scale(battle_salience)", model, 0.16)
  refit(update(formula,  ~ . + scale(journey_salience)), "scale(journey_salience)", model, 0.6)
}

backers.refit = function(formula, key, model, rr_del = 1.0) {
  new.mod = glmmTMB(formula, data = projects.b, family = "truncated_nbinom2")
  print(anova(new.mod, model, test="Chisq"))
  fe = fixef(new.mod)$cond[key]
  # intercept = fixef(new.mod)$cond["(Intercept)"] \t Intercept: {round(intercept, 5)}
  print(glue("{key}:\t beta: {round(fe,5)}\t rate ratio: {round((exp(fe*rr_del) - 1)*100, 1)}%"))
}
addMetaphors(backers.formula, backers.refit, backers.mod)

Incident Rate Ratio

Projects with any metaphor are expected to have 6.9% more donors than projects with no metaphors at all, with other predictor values remaining constant.
